		<div id="comment_body_64561179"><p>Certainly, citation below, you can thank me later:</p><p>Reuters is out with it&rsquo;s annual list of the world&rsquo;s most innovative universities.</p><p>The list is interesting in that it&rsquo;s international and that it measures university outputs such as patents and original published research and impact on commerce &ndash; drivers of economic vitality.</p><p>That&rsquo;s interesting on its own. But what&rsquo;s remarkable is the depth and consistent domination of American universities.</p><p>The top five most innovative universities on the planet, according to Reuters, are in the United States. Eight of the top 10 are American. Overall, 46 of the top 100 fly the star spangled banner. Germany, the runner-up, had nine in the top 100. France has eight while Japan, the U.K. and South Korea each have six. America&rsquo;s most identified economic adversary, China, has four. Again, there are 46 in the U.S.<br><a href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/dereknewton/2019/10/28/american-universities-still-lead-the-world-in-innovation-impact/" title="forbes.com">https://www.forbes.com/sites/d...</a> [forbes.com]</p></div>
